Asset Returns and Asset Diversification

Author

Edward Vytlacil

Published

February 9, 2024

Intro

This document contains code used to create figures related to the asset return example (Example 4) of Handout 1.

Load Libraries

Base R includes the ability to make figures, though we typically use the function ggplot from package ggplot2 to make figures. We now load the ggplot2 library. You need to first install the library if you have not done so previously.

# install.packages("ggplot2")
library(ggplot2)

Hypothetical Example of Asset Prices

We now create a data frame containing hypothetical expected returns and variance of returns for three assets.

Asset <- c("A", "B", "C") 
Er      <- c(0.12,0.12,0.20)
Var     <- c(0.0025,0.01,0.04)

df <- data.frame(Asset,Er,Var)
df
  Asset   Er    Var
1     A 0.12 0.0025
2     B 0.12 0.0100
3     C 0.20 0.0400

Figure Showing Risk-Return Tradeoff

The following figure plots the expected return and variance of return (risk) for each of the three hypothetical assets.

ggplot(df, aes(x = Var, y = Er, color = Asset)) +
  geom_point(size = 9) + theme_bw(base_size = 22)+
  theme_bw() + ggtitle("Risk-Return Tradeoff") +
  xlab("Variance") + ylab("Expected Returns")

Calculating Sharpe Ratio

An investor who desires higher expected return but dislikes risk (variance of returns) would prefer asset AA to BB as AA has the same expected return as asset BB but is less risky. Whether an investor who desires higher expected return but dislikes risk would prefer asset CC to asset AA is not clear, as AA has lower expected return but also lower risk than CC. One common measure that balances the tradeoff between expected return and risk is the Sharpe Ratio, with the Sharpe Ratio for asset jj defined as: Sj=ð¼(rjârf)Var(rjârf)S_j =\frac{\mathbb E(r_j-r_f)}{\sqrt{\mbox{Var}(r_{j}-r_{f})}} where rjr_j is the return on asset jj and rfr_f is the risk free rate. Taking rf=0.02r_f=0.02, and treating rfr_f as a constant, we have Var(rjârf)=(r_{j}-r_{f})=Var(rj)(r_j). We now compute the Sharpe ratio for our three assets.

r_f <- 0.02
df$Sharpe <- (df$Er-r_f)/sqrt(df$Var)
df
  Asset   Er    Var Sharpe
1     A 0.12 0.0025    2.0
2     B 0.12 0.0100    1.0
3     C 0.20 0.0400    0.9

Figures For Asset Diversification

An investor would prefer asset AA to BB as AA has the same expected return as asset BB but is less risky. However, even though asset AA is less risky then asset BB, including both assets in the portfolio may result in lower risk than holding asset AA alone. Suppose the investor creates a portfolio that invests fraction Ï\omega in asset AA and fraction 1âÏ1-\omega in investment BB. Then return on the portfolio is given by rP=ÏârA+(1âÏ)ârB r_P = \omega \cdot r_A + (1-\omega) \cdot r_B Using the rules for expected value and variance of a sum from Handout 1, we have that the expected value of the returns on the portfolio is given by ð¼[rP]=Ïâð¼[rA]+(1âÏ)âð¼[rB] \mathbb{E}[r_P] = \omega \cdot \mathbb{E}[r_A] + (1-\omega) \cdot \mathbb{E}[r_B] while the variance of the returns on the portfolio is given by} Var(rP)=Ï2âVar(rA)+(1âÏ)2âVar(rB)+2âÏâ(1âÏ)âCov(rA,rB). \mbox{Var}(r_P) =\omega^2 \cdot \mbox{Var}(r_A)+(1-\omega)^2\cdot \mbox{Var}(r_B) + 2 \cdot \omega \cdot (1-\omega) \cdot \mbox{Cov}(r_A, r_B). The variance of the portfolio (and the extent to which including asset BB in the portfolio diversifies risk) depends crucially on the covariance in returns. The smaller Cov(rA,rB)\mbox{Cov}(r_A,r_B), the more including asset BB in the portfolio hedges the risk from assset AA. If the correlation in returns is sufficiently high, then including both assets will not diversify risk. We now plot the variance of portfolio returns as a function of Ï\omega (fraction invested in asset AA), for three alternative values of Cov(rA,rB)\mbox{Cov}(r_A,r_B). Note that the code uses a user-defined function for the variance of returns on the portfolio.

# function returning variance of return on portfolio
# as function of omega and covariance of returns
f.var <- function(w,cov_AB){w^2*Var[1] +(1-w)^2*Var[2] +2* w *(1 - w)*cov_AB}

# suppose Cov(r_A,r_B)=-0.0045, negatively correlated returns.
ggplot(data.frame(x = c(0, 1)),   aes(x=x))+ theme_bw(base_size = 12)+
  stat_function(fun=f.var,args=list(cov_AB=-0.0045)) +  
  labs(title=expression(paste("Cov(",r[A],",",r[B],") = -0.0045")))+
  scale_x_continuous(name="Fraction Invested in Asset A vs B",limits=c(0, 1))+
  scale_y_continuous(name="Volatility (Variance) of Portfolio Returns",limits=c(0,.01),expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.01)))

# suppose Cov(r_A,r_B)=0, uncorrelated  returns.
ggplot(data.frame(x = c(0, 1)),   aes(x=x))+ theme_bw(base_size = 12)+
  stat_function(fun=f.var,args=list(cov_AB=0)) +  
  labs(title=expression(paste("Cov(",r[A],",",r[B],") = 0")))+
  scale_x_continuous(name="Fraction Invested in Asset A vs B",limits=c(0, 1))+
  scale_y_continuous(name="Volatility (Variance) of Portfolio Returns",limits=c(0,.01),expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.01)))

# suppose Cov(r_A,r_B)=0.0045, positively correlated returns.
ggplot(data.frame(x = c(0, 1)),   aes(x=x))+ theme_bw(base_size = 12)+
  stat_function(fun=f.var,args=list(cov_AB=0.0045)) +  
  labs(title=expression(paste("Cov(",r[A],",",r[B],") = 0.0045")))+
  scale_x_continuous(name="Fraction Invested in Asset A vs B",limits=c(0, 1))+
  scale_y_continuous(name="Volatility (Variance) of Portfolio Returns",limits=c(0,.01),expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.01)))

Now consider a portfolio that invests fraction fraction Ï\omega in asset AA and fraction 1âÏ1-\omega in investment CC: rP=ÏârA+(1âÏ)ârC r_P = \omega \cdot r_A + (1-\omega) \cdot r_C Since ð¼(rA)â ð¼(rC)\mathbb{E}(r_A) \ne \mathbb{E}(r_C), both the expected return and the variance of returns on the portfolio depends on Ï\omega. We now plot the expected returns and variance of returns as a function of Ï\omega, using a different way to plot the figure in order to include both expected returns and variance of returns. In particular, we create a new data frame where each row corresponds to to a different value of Ï\omega, and the columns include the expected return and variance of returns at that value of Ï\omega. We create the figure supposing Cov(rA,rC)=â0.0045\mbox{Cov}(r_A,r_C)=-0.0045.

omega <- seq(from = 0, to = 1, length.out = 1000)
er_A <- df[df$Asset=="A",]$Er
er_C <- df[df$Asset=="C",]$Er
var_A <- df[df$Asset=="A",]$Var
var_C <- df[df$Asset=="C",]$Var
covAC <- -0.0045
df2 <- data.frame(w = omega)
df2$er_p  <-  df2$w * er_A + (1-df2$w) * er_C
df2$var_p <-  df2$w^2*var_A +(1-df2$w)^2*var_C +2* df2$w *(1 - df2$w)*covAC

ggplot() + geom_point(data = df2,
                      aes(x = var_p, y = er_p, color = w)) +
  theme_bw() +
  ggtitle("Possible Portfolios Comprised of Assets A and C") +
  xlab("Volatility (Variance)") +
  ylab("Expected Returns")

## Intro

This document contains code used to create figures related to the asset return example (Example 4) of [Handout 1](https://edward-vytlacil.github.io/Econ136/Handouts/Handout_1_Review_Rules_Exp_Var_Spring_2024.pdf).

## Load Libraries

Base **R** includes the ability to make figures, though we typically use the function `ggplot` from package `ggplot2` to make figures. We now load the ``ggplot2`` library.
You need to first install the library if you have not done so previously.

```{r}
# install.packages("ggplot2")
library(ggplot2)
```

## Hypothetical Example of Asset Prices

We now create a data frame containing hypothetical expected returns and variance of returns for three assets.

```{r}
Asset <- c("A", "B", "C") 
Er      <- c(0.12,0.12,0.20)
Var     <- c(0.0025,0.01,0.04)

df <- data.frame(Asset,Er,Var)
df
```

## Figure Showing Risk-Return Tradeoff

The following figure plots the expected return and variance of return (risk) for each of the three hypothetical assets.

```{r}
ggplot(df, aes(x = Var, y = Er, color = Asset)) +
  geom_point(size = 9) + theme_bw(base_size = 22)+
  theme_bw() + ggtitle("Risk-Return Tradeoff") +
  xlab("Variance") + ylab("Expected Returns")
```

## Calculating Sharpe Ratio

An investor who desires higher expected return but dislikes risk (variance
of returns) would prefer asset $A$ to $B$ as $A$ has the same expected return as
asset $B$ but is less risky. Whether an investor who desires higher expected
return but dislikes risk would prefer asset $C$ to asset $A$ is not clear, as $A$ has
lower expected return but also lower risk than $C$. One common measure that
balances the tradeoff between expected return and risk is the Sharpe Ratio, with the Sharpe Ratio for asset $j$ defined as:
$$S_j =\frac{\mathbb E(r_j-r_f)}{\sqrt{\mbox{Var}(r_{j}-r_{f})}}$$
where $r_j$ is the return on asset $j$ and $r_f$ is the risk free rate.  Taking $r_f=0.02$, and treating $r_f$ as a constant, we have Var$(r_{j}-r_{f})=$Var$(r_j)$.  We now
compute the Sharpe ratio for our three assets.
```{r}
r_f <- 0.02
df$Sharpe <- (df$Er-r_f)/sqrt(df$Var)
df
```


## Figures For Asset Diversification

An investor would prefer asset $A$ to $B$ as $A$ has the same expected return as
asset $B$ but is less risky.  However,  even though asset $A$ is less risky then asset $B$, including both assets in the portfolio may result in lower risk than holding asset $A$ alone. Suppose the investor creates a portfolio that invests fraction $\omega$ in asset $A$ and fraction $1-\omega$ in
investment $B$.  Then  return on the portfolio is given by 
$$ r_P  = \omega \cdot r_A +  (1-\omega) \cdot r_B$$
Using the rules for expected value and variance of
a sum from [Handout 1](https://edward-vytlacil.github.io/Econ136/Handouts/Handout_1_Review_Rules_Exp_Var_Spring_2024.pdf),
we have that the
 expected value of the returns on the portfolio is given by
$$ \mathbb{E}[r_P]   = \omega \cdot \mathbb{E}[r_A] +  (1-\omega) \cdot \mathbb{E}[r_B]$$
while the variance  of the returns on the portfolio is given by}
$$ \mbox{Var}(r_P)  =\omega^2 \cdot \mbox{Var}(r_A)+(1-\omega)^2\cdot \mbox{Var}(r_B) + 2 \cdot  \omega \cdot (1-\omega) \cdot \mbox{Cov}(r_A, r_B).
$$
The variance of the portfolio (and the extent to which including asset $B$ in the portfolio diversifies risk) depends crucially on the covariance in returns.  The smaller $\mbox{Cov}(r_A,r_B)$, the more
including asset $B$ in the portfolio hedges the risk from
assset $A$. If the correlation in returns is sufficiently
high, then including both assets will not diversify 
risk. We now plot the variance of portfolio returns as a function of $\omega$ (fraction invested in asset $A$), for three alternative values of $\mbox{Cov}(r_A,r_B)$.  Note that
the code uses a user-defined function for the variance
of returns on the portfolio.

```{r}
# function returning variance of return on portfolio
# as function of omega and covariance of returns
f.var <- function(w,cov_AB){w^2*Var[1] +(1-w)^2*Var[2] +2* w *(1 - w)*cov_AB}

# suppose Cov(r_A,r_B)=-0.0045, negatively correlated returns.
ggplot(data.frame(x = c(0, 1)),   aes(x=x))+ theme_bw(base_size = 12)+
  stat_function(fun=f.var,args=list(cov_AB=-0.0045)) +  
  labs(title=expression(paste("Cov(",r[A],",",r[B],") = -0.0045")))+
  scale_x_continuous(name="Fraction Invested in Asset A vs B",limits=c(0, 1))+
  scale_y_continuous(name="Volatility (Variance) of Portfolio Returns",limits=c(0,.01),expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.01)))

# suppose Cov(r_A,r_B)=0, uncorrelated  returns.
ggplot(data.frame(x = c(0, 1)),   aes(x=x))+ theme_bw(base_size = 12)+
  stat_function(fun=f.var,args=list(cov_AB=0)) +  
  labs(title=expression(paste("Cov(",r[A],",",r[B],") = 0")))+
  scale_x_continuous(name="Fraction Invested in Asset A vs B",limits=c(0, 1))+
  scale_y_continuous(name="Volatility (Variance) of Portfolio Returns",limits=c(0,.01),expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.01)))

# suppose Cov(r_A,r_B)=0.0045, positively correlated returns.
ggplot(data.frame(x = c(0, 1)),   aes(x=x))+ theme_bw(base_size = 12)+
  stat_function(fun=f.var,args=list(cov_AB=0.0045)) +  
  labs(title=expression(paste("Cov(",r[A],",",r[B],") = 0.0045")))+
  scale_x_continuous(name="Fraction Invested in Asset A vs B",limits=c(0, 1))+
  scale_y_continuous(name="Volatility (Variance) of Portfolio Returns",limits=c(0,.01),expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.01)))

```

Now consider a portfolio that invests fraction   fraction $\omega$ in asset $A$ and fraction $1-\omega$ in
investment $C$:
$$ r_P  = \omega \cdot r_A +  (1-\omega) \cdot r_C$$
Since $\mathbb{E}(r_A) \ne \mathbb{E}(r_C)$, both the expected return and the variance
of returns on the portfolio depends on $\omega$.  We now plot the expected returns and variance
of returns as a function of $\omega$, using a different way to plot the figure in order to include
both expected returns and variance
of returns.  In particular, we create a new data frame where each row corresponds to to a 
different value of $\omega$, and the columns include the expected return and variance of returns
at that value of $\omega$.  We create the figure supposing $\mbox{Cov}(r_A,r_C)=-0.0045$.

```{r}
omega <- seq(from = 0, to = 1, length.out = 1000)
er_A <- df[df$Asset=="A",]$Er
er_C <- df[df$Asset=="C",]$Er
var_A <- df[df$Asset=="A",]$Var
var_C <- df[df$Asset=="C",]$Var
covAC <- -0.0045
df2 <- data.frame(w = omega)
df2$er_p  <-  df2$w * er_A + (1-df2$w) * er_C
df2$var_p <-  df2$w^2*var_A +(1-df2$w)^2*var_C +2* df2$w *(1 - df2$w)*covAC

ggplot() + geom_point(data = df2,
                      aes(x = var_p, y = er_p, color = w)) +
  theme_bw() +
  ggtitle("Possible Portfolios Comprised of Assets A and C") +
  xlab("Volatility (Variance)") +
  ylab("Expected Returns")
```
